hnic nationhood. Phi Hong Su's rigorous ethnography unpacks this intuition. In absorbing prose, Su reveals how these Cold War compatriots enact palpable social boundaries in everyday life. This book uncovers how 20th-century state formation and international migration—together, border crossings—generate enduring migrant classifications. In doing so, border crossings fracture shared ethnic, national, and religious identities in enduring ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aNationalismzGermanyzBerlin. 0aNationalismzVietnam. 0aVietnamesezGermanyzBerlinxEthnic identity. 0aVietnamesezGermanyzBerlinxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aCold War.  acontract workers.  aethnicity.  ainternational migration.  anationhood and nationalism.  arefugees.  astate formation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363015440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503630154423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503630154/original  a978-3-11-073914-5  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles